            {
                "s2_paper_id": "a55a191ba1537f8c8f579e9462a7e13d7213b7d2",
                "title": "Properties of MgB2 films grown at various temperatures by hybrid physical\u2013chemical vapour deposition",
                "year": 2008,
                "venue": "",
                "citation_count": 13,
                "reference_count": 22,
                "abstract": "A hybrid physical\u2013chemical vapour deposition (HPCVD) system consisting of separately controlled Mg-source heater and substrate heater is used to grow MgB2 thin films and thick films at various temperatures. We are able to grow superconducting MgB2 thin films at temperatures as low as 350\u2009\u00b0C with a Tc0 of 35.5 K. MgB2 films up to 4 \u00b5m in thickness grown at 550\u2009\u00b0C have Jc over 106 A cm\u22122 at 5 K and zero applied field. The low deposition temperature of MgB2 films is desirable for all-MgB2 tunnel junctions and MgB2 thick films are important for applications in coated conductors.",
